<DOC><DOCNO> AP890510-0177 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-10-89 2032EST</FILEID><FIRST>r w AM-ArmsSales     05-10 0170</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Arms Sales,160</SECOND><HEAD>Pentagon Notifies Congress of Arms Sales</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Pentagon notified Congress Wednesday thtit had approved a series of arms deals with three Middle Easterncountries and Taiwan.   Assuming there are no congressional objections, the Pentagonsaid it intended to sell Hawk surface-to-air missiles to Egypt;maintenance and training services for F-5 and F-15 jet fighters toSaudi Arabia, and rocket artillery launchers to Bahrain.   Taiwan is being offered 88 Standard ship-defense missiles for$44 million, the Pentagon added.   By far the largest of the transactions are the deals with SaudiArabia. The two maintenance and service contracts for the fighters,including their Sparrow and Sidewinder missiles, will total about$500 million, the Pentagon said.   The deal with Egypt is valued at $51 million and will include150 Hawk missiles. The deal with Bahrain covers seven so-calledMultiple Launch Rocket Systems and will total about $93 million.   The Mideast transactions ``will not affect the basic militarybalance in the region,'' the Pentagon informed Congress.</TEXT></DOC>